<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-slopefields-1">
  <title>What a Slope Field Represents</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What does each little line segment in a slope field for the equation 
      <m>y' = f(x,y)</m> represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The slope <m>f(x,y)</m> of a solution curve passing through that point.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A slope field assigns a tiny line with slope <m>f(x,y)</m> at 
          each point <m>(x,y)</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The value of <m>y</m> at that point.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the line segment encodes slope, not height.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The second derivative <m>y''</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—slope fields visualize only the first derivative.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-slopefields-2">
  <title>Reading Solution Behavior</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      When sketching a solution curve on a slope field, what rule should you follow?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>Draw a curve that stays tangent to the nearby line segments.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. A solution must follow the slopes shown in the field.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Draw any smooth curve that goes through the initial point.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the slope field dictates the direction the curve must follow.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Draw a horizontal line through the initial point.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—only equations with <m>y'=0</m> would behave like this.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-slopefields-3">
  <title>Using an Initial Condition</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What does an initial condition like <m>y(x_0)=y_0</m> represent on a slope field?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The point where the solution curve must begin.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. From that point, the solution must follow the slopes in the 
          field.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A point where the slope must be zero.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the slope there is given by <m>f(x_0,y_0)</m>, not necessarily zero.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A value of <m>x</m> where the solution does not exist.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—initial conditions specify where the solution <em>does</em> exist and begin.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-slopefields-4">
  <title>Interpreting a Slope Field Example</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the equation <m>y' = xy</m>, what does the slope field suggest about 
      the solution with initial condition <m>y(0)=0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The solution remains the constant function <m>y=0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. At all points where <m>y=0</m>, the slope <m>xy = 0</m>, so the 
          zero solution stays horizontal.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The solution grows rapidly for <m>x&gt;0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this happens only for initial conditions with <m>y&gt;0</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The solution decreases for all <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—zero slope implies constant behavior.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

  <!-- EXERCISE 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="value-of-slopefields">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What do you see as the value in slope fields?  
        What role does technology play in this concept?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Slope fields allow us to visualize the behavior of solutions to a 
        first‑order differential equation <m>y' = f(x,y)</m> even when 
        no explicit formula for the solution is available.  
        Each short line segment in the field shows the slope that a solution 
        curve must follow at that point, helping us understand qualitative 
        features such as growth, decay, stability, or how tiny changes in an
        initial condition affect the solution.  
        Slope fields provide insight “even when we cannot explicitly solve 
        the equation.”
      </p>

      <p>
        Technology plays an essential role because manually drawing enough
        slope segments to reveal meaningful structure is impractical.  
        The text notes that “in practice, one does not do this by hand;  
        a computer can do the drawing,” allowing us to plot dense slope fields 
        and overlay solution curves quickly and accurately.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- EXERCISE 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="picards-theorem">
    <statement>
      <p>
        In your own words, what does 
        <url href="https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/slopefields_section.html#slope_picardthm">Picard's theorem</url>
        say?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Picard’s theorem guarantees that if the function <m>f(x,y)</m> in the 
        differential equation <m>y' = f(x,y)</m> behaves nicely—specifically,
        if it is continuous and satisfies a suitable condition ensuring it 
        doesn’t change too abruptly—then two important things happen near a chosen 
        point <m>(x_0, y_0)</m>:  
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            There exists a solution curve passing through <m>(x_0, y_0)</m>.  
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            That solution is unique; no other solution curve through that same 
            initial point can exist.  
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        In other words, the theorem formalizes what slope fields visually suggest:
        given a starting point, the direction field forms a single “path” the 
        solution must follow.  This connects the geometric picture to a rigorous 
        existence‑and‑uniqueness guarantee.  
      </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>

